<section xml:id="sec-limits-and-integration">
  <title>Limits and integration</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use limits to describe infinite processes and long-term behavior.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret Riemann sums as limits of increasingly fine partitions to approximate area.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize that not every function is integrable and understand why extreme examples fail.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Zeno's arrow paradox
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Limits at infinity
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Sums of powers:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^n c \amp = c n </mrow>
        <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^n k \amp = \frac{n(n+1)}{2} \approx \frac{1}{2} n^2 </mrow>
        <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^n k^2 \amp = \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6} \approx \frac{1}{3} n^3 </mrow>
        <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^n k^3 \amp = \left(\frac{n(n+1)}{2}\right)^2 \approx \frac{1}{4} n^4 </mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Riemann sum to compute <m>\DS\int_{0}^{1} x\dd{x}</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Some functions aren't integrable: great example is the Dirichlet function
        <me>
          D(x)=\begin{cases}1 \amp \text{if $x$ is rational}\\ 0 \amp \text{if $x$ is irrational}\end{cases}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
